<article>
    <h1>PASHA CAS, 25&#xD;&#xA;Street artist, Kaza&#xAD;khstan</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201219/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-19"><time>2020-12-19</time></a>
        - <span>SPECIAL REPORT</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>The award-win­ning street artist is known to draw at­ten­tion to Kaza­khstan’s so­cial prob­lems through his works. He pro­duced one of his most fa­mous – and shocking – works in 2013, when he hung a man­nequin un­der a bill­board in Al­maty in a bid to raise aware­ness about sui­cide preven­tion.</p>
    <p>Pasha, who is also ac­tive in Rus­sia, be­came the first Kazakh artist to win the Sergey Kuryokhin Award last year. He was awarded for a paint­ing he did at a pub­lic space in St Petersburg, of a girl dressed in clothes of yore dec­o­rat­ing a Christ­mas tree – his de­pic­tion of Rus­sia’s Soviet past.</p>
    <p>In May, he paid trib­ute to med­i­cal work­ers risk­ing their lives to treat Covid-19 pa­tients with a video of him­self, al­most naked, ly­ing still and sur­rounded by peo­ple in blue sur­gi­cal gowns, also pros­trate and im­mo­bile, on a round patch of green meant to por­tray the globe.</p>

